dataIdInfo.idAbs:
NaPALIS:

NaPALIS is a web-based centralised system and database for all Land Information New Zealand (LINZ) and Department of Conservation (DOC) administered land. It allows authorized users to reference and maintain information about land.

Protected Area:

A protected area is a clearly defined geographical space, recognised, dedicated and managed, through legal or other effective means, to achieve the long term conservation of nature with associated ecosystem services and cultural values.

There are around 60 different types of protected areain New Zealand. The most important are:

  • National Parks

  • Conservation Parks

  • Nature Reserves

  • Scientific Reserves

  • Scenic Reserves

  • Historic Reserves

  • Recreation (and other) Reserves

  • Other Public Conservation Land

These categories vary in their conservation value and the opportunities they provide for outdoor recreation. “Other Public Conservation Land” includes over 7,000 protected areas, and “Recreation (and other) Reserves” combines many of the smaller reserve classes.

New Zealand’s protected areas are managed under six main laws:

  • Conservation Act 1987

  • National Parks Act 1980

  • Reserves Act 1977

  • Wildlife Act 1953

  • Marine Reserves Act 1971

  • Marine Mammals Protection Act 1979.

attr.attrdef: A timestamp that defines the date the land parcel was created. Most parcels created pre-NaPALIS will have a “null” field (creation date unknown).
A timestamp that defines the date the land parcel is re-defined prior to archiving.
This is the legal status of a Public Conservation Land parcel within NaPALIS. Could be Conservation Area, Marginal Strip, Marine Area, National Park, Reserve or Wildlife Area.

Prior to NaPALIS, the Department of Conservation maintained a "Land Register" containing all parcels of Public Conservation Land. These land parcels were known as "Conservation Units" being either a standard grouping of parcels or individual parcels determined by uniqueness relating to status, name, and/or purpose. Each Conservation Unit was given a unique name.
Legislative acts are subdivided into relevant parts called "sections". This field indicates the relevant Section within the relevant Act

A "vested" reseve means a reserve in which certain terms of ownership is set out in the Reserves Act (an administering body - usually a territorial authority) although residual ownership of the reserve remains with the Crown.
In certain circumstances a land parcel may have a primary legislative status while it may also have a secondary status which is deemed to be "overlying".
Reserve classification is a process under the Reserves Act 1977 for putting a reserve into a class under that Act; or specifying the type of a scenic, or government/local purpose reserve.

The characteristic appearance or visible form of a geographic object as represented on a map. A GIS uses points, lines, and polygons to represent the shapes of geographic objects. This field is automatically generated by ArcGIS.
This is the internal area of a polygon in internal units. It is automatically generated in ArcGIS (“Points” and “lines” do not have a shape area)

dataLineage.statement: The data in this dataset was initially derived from protected land information/records held by former parent agencies of the Department of Conservation (DOC) (ie mainly Lands and Survey Department, New Zealand Forest Service , New Zealand Wildlife Service). Since the formation of DOC these records have been maintained by the department through its day-to-day management of protected lands in New Zealand.
